Welcome to notebook four of the Java track. Notebook three gave us collections. This notebook turns those collections into pipelines. The way modern Java code actually iterates, filters, transforms, and aggregates data. If you have written Python list comprehensions, or Spark resilient distributed dataset operators, or chained array methods in JavaScript, you already know the mental model. Java's version is called the Stream application programming interface, and it sits on top of two newer language features. Lambdas, and method references.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, lambdas. The arrow syntax, and what they replace. Method references, the double colon shorthand. The four core functional interfaces, namely Function, Predicate, Consumer, and Supplier, plus the two argument variants like BiFunction and BiPredicate. How to write your own functional interface using the at sign Functional Interface annotation. How lambdas capture surrounding variables, and the effectively final rule. Then streams. The pipeline model, with a source stage, intermediate operations, and a terminal operation. How to create streams from collections, from literals, from numeric ranges, and from infinite generators. The intermediate operations like filter, map, flat map, distinct, sorted, peek, limit, and skip. The terminal operations like collect, reduce, for each, count, any match, find first, and the min and max operations. The Collectors utility class, with to list, to set, to map, grouping by, partitioning by, and joining. Parallel streams, when they help and when they hurt. And finally, the Optional type, the type safe alternative to null, with its map, flat map, filter, or else, or else get, or else throw, and if present methods.

Let us start with lambdas. A lambda expression is a short inline function you can pass around like any other value. Before Java eight, the way to pass behaviour to a method was an anonymous inner class. You typed new of some interface name, with the override of the single abstract method written out by hand. That was about five lines of ceremony for one expression of actual logic. Lambdas reduce all of that to one line.

The lambda syntax is parameters, arrow, body. The arrow is a hyphen followed by a greater than sign. If your lambda takes no parameters, you write empty parentheses on the left of the arrow. If it takes one parameter, the parentheses around the parameter are optional. If it takes multiple parameters, the parentheses are required. The parameter types are inferred from the context by default, but you are allowed to write them explicitly if you want. The body of the lambda is either a single expression, in which case its value is returned automatically, or a block in braces, in which case you need an explicit return statement for non void lambdas.

The compiler treats a lambda as a value of some functional interface type. A functional interface is any interface with exactly one abstract method. The compiler infers which interface from the surrounding context. If you assign a lambda to a variable of type Comparator of String, the compiler reads Comparator's single abstract method, sees that it takes two strings and returns an int, and binds the lambda accordingly.

When a lambda does nothing but call an existing method, you can replace it with a method reference. A method reference is the double colon shorthand. It comes in four flavours.

Class colon colon static method is a reference to a static method on a class. So Integer colon colon parse int is a function that takes a string and returns the result of calling Integer dot parseInt on it. Instance colon colon instance method is a reference to a method on a specific instance. So the variable prefix dot concat, written as prefix colon colon concat, is a function that takes a string and returns prefix concatenated with that string. Class colon colon instance method is the most subtle one. It refers to an instance method, but uses the receiver as the first argument. So String colon colon length is a function that takes a String and returns its length. And finally, Class colon colon new is a constructor reference. ArrayList colon colon new is a supplier that produces a new ArrayList on demand.

Method references are not faster than the equivalent lambda. They are just shorter and often clearer. Use them when the lambda body is nothing more than forwarding to a single method.

Now the four core functional interfaces. The java util function package ships about forty functional interfaces, but four of them cover the vast majority of real code. Memorise the shape of each one, because they show up in every Stream operation.

Function of T comma R is the transformation shape. Its abstract method is apply, which takes a T and returns an R. Use it when you transform a value into another value. Predicate of T is the testing shape. Its abstract method is test, which takes a T and returns a boolean. Use it for filtering and matching. Consumer of T is the side effect shape. Its abstract method is accept, which takes a T and returns void. Use it when you do something with a value but produce no result, like printing or logging. Supplier of T is the production shape. Its abstract method is get, which takes nothing and returns a T. Use it for lazy computation of a default, or for factory style construction.

Two argument variants exist for the same shapes. BiFunction of T comma U comma R takes two arguments and returns a result. BiPredicate of T comma U takes two arguments and returns a boolean. BiConsumer of T comma U takes two arguments and returns void. There are also primitive specialised variants, like Int Function and Int Predicate, that avoid boxing when you are working with int, long, or double values. Use the primitive variants in hot loops.

Any interface with exactly one abstract method can be used as a lambda target, including interfaces you write yourself. The at sign Functional Interface annotation is optional, but you should use it on interfaces meant for lambda use. It documents the intent and makes the compiler enforce the single abstract method rule. If you accidentally add a second abstract method to an annotated interface, the compiler errors out. Default methods on the interface do not count toward the single abstract method rule, so you can layer convenience helpers on top.

A subtle rule about lambdas and the enclosing scope. A lambda can reference local variables from the enclosing method, but only if those variables are effectively final. Effectively final means assigned exactly once and never reassigned. The compiler will reject a lambda that reads a variable you reassign later in the method, and it will reject a lambda that tries to assign to a captured variable inside its own body.

This restriction exists because lambdas can outlive the method that created them. Imagine you pass a lambda to an executor that runs it on another thread, then the original method returns. At that moment, the local variables of the original method are gone. The lambda kept a snapshot of the captured values at capture time. Allowing reassignment would create confusing, hard to debug inconsistencies between what the original method sees and what the lambda sees.

The standard workaround, when you really do need a mutable captured value, is to use a single element array. The array reference itself is effectively final. Mutating its contents is fine. So var counter equals new int array of zero, then a lambda that does counter zero plus plus, compiles and works.

Now streams. A stream is a one time use pipeline that pulls elements through a chain of operations. It is not a collection. It does not store the elements. It is a description of work to do, applied lazily when a terminal operation kicks off the pipeline.

Every stream pipeline has three stages. The source is where the elements come from. Usually that is collection dot stream. The intermediate operations are the middle stages, like filter, map, and sorted. Each intermediate operation returns a new stream and does nothing until a terminal operation runs. Intermediate operations are lazy. The terminal operation is the final stage. It triggers the pipeline, pulls every element through, and produces a result or a side effect. Terminal operations are eager.

A stream can be traversed exactly once. After a terminal operation runs, the stream is spent. Any further operation on the same stream throws an illegal state exception. This is different from a Python iterator, which works the same way, but different from a Scala collection, which you can iterate multiple times. If you need to iterate multiple times, hold the collection and call stream on it each time.

There are several ways to create a stream. The most common is collection dot stream, which produces a stream from any collection. The Stream dot of static method takes a varargs of elements and returns a stream over them. The Int Stream dot range method gives you a numeric stream from a start, inclusive, to an end, exclusive. The Int Stream dot range Closed method makes the end inclusive instead. For infinite streams, the Stream dot iterate method takes a seed and a unary operator, and produces an unbounded stream. The Stream dot generate method takes a supplier and produces an unbounded stream by calling the supplier on demand. Infinite streams must be bounded with limit before a terminal operation, or the pipeline will never finish.

Intermediate operations transform one stream into another, and they are lazy. The most important ones are filter, which takes a predicate and keeps only the elements that match. Map, which takes a function and transforms every element. Flat map, which takes a function from element to stream, and flattens the resulting stream of streams into one stream. Distinct, which removes duplicates by equality. Sorted, with no arguments for natural order, or with a comparator for custom order. Limit, which takes the first n elements. Skip, which drops the first n elements. And peek, which lets you observe each element without modifying it, useful for debugging only, never for production logic.

Flat map deserves a moment of attention. If you have a stream of strings, where each string is a sentence, and you call map of split by space, you get a stream of arrays of strings. That is not what you wanted. If you call flat map of array dot stream of split by space, the inner arrays get flattened, and you get a single stream of words. Flat map is map followed by flatten.

Terminal operations trigger the pipeline and produce a result. The to list method, added in Java sixteen, is the modern way to collect a stream to an unmodifiable list. The collect method takes a collector, which we will get to in a moment. The count method returns a long with the number of elements. The for each method runs a consumer on every element, for side effects. The reduce method folds the stream to a single value, given an identity and a binary operator. The any match, all match, and none match methods take a predicate and return a boolean, short circuiting as soon as the answer is known. The find first and find any methods return an Optional of the first or any element that survives the pipeline. The min and max methods take a comparator and return an Optional of the smallest or largest element.

Notice that min, max, find first, find any, and reduce without an identity all return Optional. The reason is that the stream might be empty, in which case there is no answer. Returning Optional forces the caller to handle the empty case explicitly, rather than getting back a default like zero, which would silently hide bugs.

For more flexible aggregation, the Collectors utility class provides ready made collectors. The to list collector produces a list. The to set collector produces a set. The to map collector takes a key extractor and a value extractor and produces a map. The grouping by collector takes a classifier function and produces a map from key to list of elements, like a SQL group by. The partitioning by collector takes a predicate and produces a map from boolean to list, splitting the stream into two buckets. The joining collector concatenates the stream into a single string, optionally with a delimiter, a prefix, and a suffix. And the counting collector counts elements within a group, often used as the downstream collector for grouping by.

Parallel streams are a one keyword optimisation. Adding dot parallel after the source, or starting from collection dot parallel stream instead of collection dot stream, splits the work across the java virtual machine's common fork join pool. Each element is processed independently, and the framework merges the partial results at the end.

Parallel streams pay off when three conditions hold. The dataset is large, typically more than ten thousand elements. The per element work is non trivial, not just incrementing a counter. And the operations are stateless and side effect free. Parallel streams hurt when the stream is small, when the collection has poor split characteristics like a linked list, or when the lambdas mutate shared state, which gives you race conditions. The rule of thumb is to default to sequential streams, and switch to parallel only after profiling tells you the work is worth parallelising.

The last topic is Optional. Tony Hoare, who invented the null reference in nineteen sixty five, famously called it his billion dollar mistake. Null is a value that compiles as any reference type, but crashes the moment you dereference it. Java still has null, because it cannot remove it for backwards compatibility, but for return values that might legitimately be absent, modern Java uses Optional of T.

An Optional of T is a small wrapper that either holds a value or is empty. The compiler forces you to acknowledge the empty case before reaching the inner value.

Creating an Optional has three forms. Optional dot of takes a non null value and wraps it. If you pass null to Optional dot of, it throws a null pointer exception. Optional dot of nullable takes a possibly null value, and either wraps it or returns an empty Optional. Optional dot empty returns the canonical empty Optional.

Reading an Optional has many methods. The is present method returns a boolean. The get method returns the inner value, but throws if the Optional is empty, so you should almost never call get directly. The if present method takes a consumer and runs it only if the value is present. The or else method returns the inner value, or a default if empty. The or else get method does the same, but takes a supplier for the default, which is evaluated lazily. The or else throw method returns the inner value, or throws an exception you supply.

The map, filter, and flat map methods let you transform inside the Optional without ever unwrapping it. Map applies a function to the inner value, returning a new Optional. Filter applies a predicate, returning the Optional unchanged if it matches, or empty otherwise. Flat map is for when your function returns an Optional itself, and you want to avoid an Optional of Optional.

The Optional contract is clear and worth memorising. Use Optional as a return type for values that may legitimately be absent. Do not use Optional for fields. Do not use Optional for method parameters. Do not use Optional inside collections. The convention exists because Optional is heavier than null, and the type system already handles those other cases. For an absent field, use a sensible default or null with a comment. For an optional parameter, use overloads. For an empty collection, return an empty list, not an Optional list.

Streams and Optional were designed to compose. Every stream terminal operation that might find nothing returns an Optional. Find first returns Optional of T. Find any returns Optional of T. Min and max return Optional of T. Reduce without an identity returns Optional of T. You can keep chaining map and filter inside the Optional, and only at the very end unwrap with or else, or else get, or else throw, or if present.

That wraps notebook four. You can now express transformations in Java the way you would write a Python list comprehension, or a Spark data frame pipeline. Streams and Optional together are the idioms you will see in every modern Java codebase, especially Spring services. Every Spring repository query returns Optional of entity. Every list endpoint returns the result of a stream collected to a list. The shapes you learned here are the shapes that drive real production Java.

Notebook five turns to the boring but essential side of any real program. Errors, files, and input output. Checked exceptions versus unchecked exceptions. The try with resources statement for safe cleanup. Writing your own custom exception types. The new input output application programming interface, with Path and Files, for reading and writing the filesystem. And a short note on serialization.
